x4freetext: The Weapons Neutron Research (WNR)
facility at the Los Alamos Neutron Science Center
(LANSCE).
54-element EJ-309 liquid scintillator array
each of which was mounted to a R4144 Hamamatsu
photomultiplier tube.
The target was an approximately 2.5 cm diameter by
2.5 cm thickness cylinder, with a total mass of
approximately 26 g. The diameter of the circular
profile of the incident neutron beam was 1.5 cm, and
thus safely within the diameter of the target itself.
Both measurements were carried out at
the 15L flight path at the Los Alamos Neutron Science
Center. The WNR white neutron source is generated via
spallation of 800 MeV protons incident on a tungsten
target. Neutrons emitted 15 degree to the left of the
incident proton beam were collimated and allowed to
impinge on a machined graphite target of natural
carbon isotopic abundance after a 21.5 m flight path.
It is a spectrum shape measurement when ENDF/B-VIII.0
values were used for calibration.
Combined statistical and systematic errors.
No corrections for gamma-ray efficiency were
employed. Corrections for the gamma transit time.
